{
  "final_answer": "## Answer\n\n### Recasting Space Segment Adjusted EBITDA Excluding Starship R&D\n\n**Reported Space Segment Adjusted EBITDA (FY2025): $653M**\n\nIf the $3,004M of Starship R&D were reclassified from a segment expense to an unallocated corporate expense, Space Segment Adjusted EBITDA would be:\n\n**$653M + $3,004M = $3,657M**\n\n### Reconciliation (in $ millions)\n\n| Line Item | As Reported | Starship R&D Reclassified to Corporate |\n|---|---:|---:|\n| Revenue | $4,086 | $4,086 |\n| Cost of revenue | (1,352) | (1,352) |\n| Research and development | (3,004) | — |\n| SG&A | (349) | (349) |\n| Impairment | (38) | (38) |\n| **Income (loss) from operations** | **(657)** | **2,347** |\n| Add: D&A | 757 | 757 |\n| Add: Share-based compensation | 515 | 515 |\n| Add: Impairment | 38 | 38 |\n| **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** | **$653** | **$3,657** |\n| Adjusted EBITDA margin | 15.98% | 89.50% |\n\n### What This Indicates About Segment-Level Profitability Presentation\n\n1. **Extreme sensitivity to allocation methodology.** A single allocation decision — whether Starship R&D sits inside the Space segment or in unallocated corporate — swings Space Segment Adjusted EBITDA by roughly **5.6x** (from $653M to $3,657M) and the segment margin from ~16% to ~90%. The reported segment profitability is therefore not a robust indicator of the underlying economics of the Space business; it is heavily dependent on management's classification choice.\n\n2. **Starship R&D dominates the segment cost structure.** Starship R&D of $3,004M equals **73.5% of Space segment revenue** and **63.3% of total Space segment costs and expenses**. The segment's reported operating loss of $(657)M is essentially a Starship R&D story — without it, the segment would have generated $2,347M of operating income on $4,086M of revenue.\n\n3. **Adjusted EBITDA masks the operating loss.** The reported $653M of positive Adjusted EBITDA is only achievable because D&A ($757M), SBC ($515M), and impairment ($38M) add-backs more than offset the $(657)M GAAP operating loss. Stripping out Starship R&D as well produces a dramatically different picture, illustrating that the non-GAAP measure is highly sensitive to which costs are allocated to the segment versus excluded via add-backs.\n\n4. **Strategic-investment framing.** Starship is a next-generation platform whose development benefits the entire enterprise (potentially the Connectivity/Starlink and AI segments as well, via launch capacity and cadence). Treating it as a segment cost makes the Space segment look marginally profitable; treating it as a corporate strategic investment would make Space look like a high-margin cash generator. The choice materially affects how investors assess segment-level unit economics and capital allocation.\n\n5. **Disclosure implication.** Because the recast consolidated financials include xAI and X Holdings under common-control accounting, and because Starship R&D is the single largest line item in the Space segment, investors should view Space Segment Adjusted EBITDA as a presentation-dependent metric rather than a clean read on the segment's standalone profitability. The filing's allocation of Starship R&D to the Space segment is a conservative choice that depresses reported segment profitability relative to an unallocated-corporate treatment.\n\n### Sources\n\n{\n  \"sources\": [\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm\",\n      \"name\": \"SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Segment Financial Information and Segment Adjusted EBITDA reconciliation\"\n    }\n  ]\n}",
